  "market_context": "ES 1-minute chart showing a consolidation range followed by an aggressive drop and an equally aggressive recovery back into the range. The analyst is illustrating a Box Setup entry scenario where standard body-based range definition would be suboptimal due to the aggressive wick action.",
  "key_observation": "When an aggressive move down is immediately reversed by an aggressive move back up, using the wick (rather than the body) as the box low provides a tighter, more accurate deviation level for re-entry.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Step 1: Identify the consolidation range low on the ES 1-minute chart where price put in a low before the aggressive sequence.",
    "Step 2: Observe the aggressive move down followed by an equally aggressive move back up into the range.",
    "Step 3: Recognize that using the candle body as the box low would place the level too high, missing the true deviation extreme.",
    "Step 4: Switch to using the wick as the range low to mark out the deviation from the range more precisely.",
    "Step 5: Wait for price to retest the wick-based level and take the entry on the tap.",
    "Step 6: Confirm price moved higher after the precise tap of the wick-defined deviation."
  ],
  "outcome": "The wick-based entry got a clean tap and price moved higher as anticipated.",
  "lessons": "In Box Setup trading, the choice between wick and body for defining range boundaries depends on context — aggressive sweep-and-recover sequences are better mapped using wicks, while ordinary consolidations are mapped using bodies, especially on lower timeframes.",
